template_id: openagreements-restrictive-covenant-delaware
name: OpenAgreements Employee Restrictive Covenant (Delaware)
category: non-compete
description: >-
  Delaware-specific employee restrictive covenant agreement built for Delaware's
  common-law reasonableness regime: there is no general Delaware non-compete
  statute, so every post-employment restraint stands or falls on the Court of
  Chancery's three-part review (reasonable in geographic scope and temporal
  duration, advancing a legitimate economic interest, and surviving a balancing
  of the equities), evaluated holistically across every dimension of the
  covenant (FP UC Holdings, LLC v. Hamilton; Sunder Energy, LLC v. Jackson). It
  provides confidentiality and trade-secret protection backstopped by the
  Delaware Uniform Trade Secrets Act (6 Del. C. §§ 2001-2007), a formation-stage
  consideration recital that names the value exchanged (Research & Trading Corp.
  v. Powell; North American Fire Ultimate Holdings, LP v. Doorly; Payscale Inc.
  v. Norman), customer and employee non-solicitation, an optional non-compete
  sized to identified legitimate interests, physician practice-covenant
  compliance that voids any practice restraint while preserving reasonably
  related damages (6 Del. C. § 2707), a home-inspector-trainee carve-out (24 Del.
  C. § 4109(d)), a Delaware choice-of-law anchor bounded by its statutory and
  conflict-of-law limits (6 Del. C. § 2708; Ascension Insurance Holdings, LLC v.
  Underwood), and a draft-the-scope reformation posture the agreement does not
  rely on because recent decisions increasingly refuse to blue-pencil an
  overbroad covenant (Kodiak Building Partners, LLC v. Adams; Intertek Testing
  Services NA, Inc. v. Eastman; Sunder Energy, LLC v. Jackson (Del. 2024)).
  Drafted as a starting point for licensed counsel review.
