    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
  - name: customer_nonsolicit_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of customer/partner non-solicitation restriction
    display_label: Customer Non-Solicitation Duration
    default: 12 months
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Delaware sets no statutory cap; a customer non-solicit tied to specific,
      identified customer relationships is the business-specific interest
      Delaware credits and is often the better instrument than a full
      non-compete. 12 months is a common, conservative duration counsel should
      size to the actual customer relationships protected.
  - name: covered_customer_period
    type: string
    description: >-
      Lookback period for determining which customers are covered by the
      non-solicitation and non-dealing restrictions.
    display_label: Covered Customer Period
    default: 12 months
    section: Customer Non-Solicitation
    default_value_rationale: >-
      12 months is the most common lookback period for customer non-solicitation
      scope.
  - name: noncompete_included
    type: boolean
    description: >-
      Whether the non-competition covenant is included. Delaware has no general
      non-compete statute; a non-compete is enforceable only to the extent it
      satisfies the Court of Chancery's three-part reasonableness review — it
      must be reasonable in geographic scope and temporal duration, advance a
      legitimate economic interest, and survive a balancing of the equities —
      evaluated holistically against every other restriction in the contract.
      This template recites the legitimate-interest basis and sizes the restraint
      to the employer's actual footprint at the drafting table, because recent
      decisions increasingly refuse to blue-pencil an overbroad covenant.
    display_label: Non-Competition Included
    default: false
    section: Non-Competition
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Conservative default. The non-compete is the most heavily scrutinized
      covenant under the Delaware reasonableness review; a customer non-solicit
      backstopped by the Delaware Uniform Trade Secrets Act often protects the
      employer as well. Include only after confirming a recognized legitimate
      interest (employer goodwill or confidential information) and sizing the
      duration and territory to the actual footprint — a court may let an
      overbroad covenant fail rather than rewrite it.
  - name: noncompete_duration
    type: string
    description: Duration of non-competition restriction
    display_label: Non-Competition Duration
    default: 12 months
    section: Non-Competition
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Delaware imposes no statutory cap on duration; the Court of Chancery weighs
      time and territory together with every other dimension against the
      employer's real legitimate interest, so there is no safe-harbor number. 12
      months is a common, conservative default counsel should size to the actual
      role and market rather than copy from another form.
  - name: territory
    type: string
    description: Geographic scope of the non-competition restriction
    display_label: Restricted Territory
    default: the geographic area in which Employee provided services
    section: Non-Competition
    default_value_rationale: >-
      Tied to the employee's actual service area. Geographic scope is the first
      prong of the Delaware reasonableness review; a narrower area genuinely
      needed to protect employer goodwill or confidential information is far
      easier to defend than a broad or nationwide ban, and an overbroad territory
      risks the whole covenant because Delaware courts increasingly decline to
      trim overreach.
  - name: competitive_business_definition
    type: string
    description: >-
      Description of the business activities that constitute competition with
